@* One sprite for every page, rendered once by _Layout: each glyph is drawn by a <use> of a symbol
   defined here, so a 500-row subtree carries one copy of each path rather than one per row, and a
   glyph is reusable across pages instead of being redefined per view. Root is an opened container,
   Branch a closed one, Leaf the terminal work item — the same Root/Branch/Leaf vocabulary the kind
   chip spells out, drawn.

   Every paint is a presentation attribute rather than a class: <use> clones a symbol into a
   shadow tree, which document stylesheets cannot select into. Only inherited properties reach
   the clone, which is why the glyphs take their colour from the host <svg>'s `fill: currentcolor`
   and everything else (the opacities, the leaf's stroked midrib) is set here on the node itself. *@
<svg class="jt-icon-sprite" aria-hidden="true" focusable="false">
	@* Both containers are drawn as a darker back plate with a lighter front panel over it — the
	   depth cue that makes a folder read as a folder at a glance instead of as a filled square.
	   The root's front panel is skewed open; the branch's is square and closed. *@
	<symbol id="jt-icon-branch" viewBox="0 0 16 16">
		<path opacity="0.55"
		      d="M1.5 4C1.5 3.31 2.06 2.75 2.75 2.75h3.19c.3 0 .59.11.81.31L8.4 4.25h4.85c.69 0 1.25.56 1.25 1.25v1.5H1.5z"/>
		<path d="M1 7c0-.69.56-1.25 1.25-1.25h11.5c.69 0 1.25.56 1.25 1.25v5.25c0 .69-.56 1.25-1.25 1.25H2.25C1.56 13.5 1 12.94 1 12.25z"/>
	</symbol>
	<symbol id="jt-icon-root" viewBox="0 0 16 16">
		<path opacity="0.55"
		      d="M1.5 4C1.5 3.31 2.06 2.75 2.75 2.75h3.19c.3 0 .59.11.81.31L8.4 4.25h4.85c.69 0 1.25.56 1.25 1.25v1.5H1.5z"/>
		<path
			d="M2.7 5.75h11.55c.82 0 1.42.77 1.21 1.56l-1.24 4.75c-.14.55-.64.94-1.21.94H1.46c-.82 0-1.42-.77-1.21-1.56l1.24-4.75c.14-.55.64-.94 1.21-.94z"/>
	</symbol>
	@* Stem first, so the blade drawn over it leaves only the exposed length outside the body. *@
	<symbol id="jt-icon-leaf" viewBox="0 0 16 16">
		<path d="M2.4 13.6 9 7" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.3" stroke-linecap="round"/>
		<path d="M13.9 2.1c.4 6-2.4 10.1-6.4 10.1-2.4 0-4-1.6-4-4 0-4 4.2-6.4 10.4-6.1Z"/>
	</symbol>
	@* Backdate: a clock wound anticlockwise. *@
	<symbol id="jt-icon-backdate" viewBox="0 0 16 16">
		<path d="M8 2.5a5.5 5.5 0 1 1-5.13 3.5" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round"/>
		<path d="M2.2 2.9v3.2h3.2" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round"
		      stroke-linejoin="round"/>
		<path d="M8 5.4V8.3l2 1.4" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round"
		      stroke-linejoin="round"/>
	</symbol>
	@* Start: a play mark leaving a starting line. Drawn as an open outline at the same 1.6 stroke as
	   Backdate so the pair reads as one set when they sit side by side in a row's action cell — and
	   deliberately unlike `jt-icon-go`, which is a solid filled sign because it labels a state rather
	   than offering an action. *@
	<symbol id="jt-icon-start" viewBox="0 0 16 16">
		<path d="M3.4 3v10" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round"/>
		<path d="M6.7 3.9 13.3 8l-6.6 4.1z" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round"
		      stroke-linejoin="round"/>
	</symbol>
	@* Finish / pause: the mirror of Start. Start puts its line on the left and moves away from it;
	   this puts the line on the right and holds two pause bars short of it — the action really is
	   both ("pause" and "finish" post to the same handler, spec §4.4), so the glyph shows work
	   stopped at the end rather than committing to one word. The bars are deliberately shorter than
	   the terminal line so three parallel strokes don't read as a bar chart. *@
	<symbol id="jt-icon-finish" viewBox="0 0 16 16">
		<path d="M5.6 4.2v7.6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round"/>
		<path d="M9.2 4.2v7.6" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round"/>
		<path d="M12.9 3v10" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round"/>
	</symbol>
	@* Readiness as a crossing signal. Stop is the raised palm of a "don't walk" hand — a held
	   position rather than an error, which is what a blocked job is. Go is a round sign with a play
	   mark knocked through it, the "you may proceed" counterpart; its knock-out is literal white
	   because it is only ever drawn inside the filled body of the sign.

	   The hand is built from four finger bars, a thumb, and a palm rather than one traced outline,
	   so it keeps its silhouette at the ~14px it is actually rendered at. *@
	<symbol id="jt-icon-stop" viewBox="0 0 16 16">
		<rect x="4.5" y="3.3" width="1.9" height="5.6" rx="0.95"/>
		<rect x="6.75" y="1.9" width="1.9" height="7" rx="0.95"/>
		<rect x="9" y="2.4" width="1.9" height="6.5" rx="0.95"/>
		<rect x="11.25" y="4" width="1.9" height="4.9" rx="0.95"/>
		<path d="M4.6 8.35a1.05 1.05 0 0 1 1.72-1.2l1.5 2.15-1.72 1.2z"/>
		<path d="M3.9 8.1h9.25v2.4a4.2 4.2 0 0 1-4.2 4.2H8.1a4.2 4.2 0 0 1-4.2-4.2z"/>
	</symbol>
	<symbol id="jt-icon-go" viewBox="0 0 16 16">
		<circle cx="8" cy="8" r="6.9"/>
		<path d="M6.5 4.9 11.4 8l-4.9 3.1z" fill="#fff"/>
	</symbol>
	@* Achievement as a family of signs: one disc, four knock-outs. They are solid filled bodies for the
	   same reason `jt-icon-go` is — they label a state rather than offer an action — and they share
	   `jt-icon-go`'s r=6.9 disc so the whole "sign" vocabulary reads as one set. The knock-outs are
	   literal white because they are only ever drawn inside the filled body.

	   The marks are chosen to be separable at the ~16px they actually render at, silhouette first:
	   a clock (queued), a disc with a wedge taken out of it (partly done), a check (done), a struck
	   bar (closed with nothing achieved). Note the family is deliberately *not* the raised palm —
	   blocked is not an achievement but an orthogonal fact about prerequisites, and a job is routinely
	   Waiting and blocked at once, so the two must never look like alternatives to each other. *@
	<symbol id="jt-icon-achievement-waiting" viewBox="0 0 16 16">
		<circle cx="8" cy="8" r="6.9"/>
		<path d="M8 4.3V8l2.6 1.5" fill="none" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"
		      stroke-linejoin="round"/>
	</symbol>
	@* The wedge runs 12 o'clock to 3 o'clock, so the disc keeps its round silhouette everywhere but the
	   bite — a pie part-way through rather than a half-disc, which loses the circle against the page. *@
	<symbol id="jt-icon-achievement-in-progress" viewBox="0 0 16 16">
		<circle cx="8" cy="8" r="6.9"/>
		<path d="M8 8V1.1A6.9 6.9 0 0 1 14.9 8z" fill="#fff"/>
	</symbol>
	<symbol id="jt-icon-achievement-success" viewBox="0 0 16 16">
		<circle cx="8" cy="8" r="6.9"/>
		<path d="m4.8 8.3 2.2 2.2 4.2-4.6" fill="none" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round"
		      stroke-linejoin="round"/>
	</symbol>
	@* A level bar, not a diagonal slash: this one glyph covers both Cancelled and Unsuccessful, and a
	   slash reads as "forbidden" — an accusation the merged state should not make about a job that was
	   simply withdrawn. A struck bar reads as "closed, nothing achieved" for either route. *@
	<symbol id="jt-icon-achievement-closed" viewBox="0 0 16 16">
		<circle cx="8" cy="8" r="6.9"/>
		<path d="M4.9 8h6.2" fill="none" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="1.6" stroke-linecap="round"/>
	</symbol>
	@* A running work session: a stopwatch, because what an active session means is that time is
	   accruing against this leaf. Solid body with white hands, following the same "filled = state"
	   rule as the rest of the sign vocabulary — deliberately unlike `jt-icon-start`, the outlined
	   play mark on the button that sits two columns away, which offers an action rather than
	   reporting one in progress.

	   The crown and stem on top are what separate it from `jt-icon-achievement-waiting`'s plain
	   disc-and-clock at the small size both render at; the two also never share a colour. *@
	<symbol id="jt-icon-active" viewBox="0 0 16 16">
		<rect x="6.4" y="0.6" width="3.2" height="1.6" rx="0.8"/>
		<rect x="7.2" y="1.8" width="1.6" height="1.6"/>
		<circle cx="8" cy="9.3" r="5.9"/>
		<path d="M8 6.1v3.2l2.2 1.3" fill="none" stroke="#fff" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-linecap="round"
		      stroke-linejoin="round"/>
	</symbol>
	@* Sessions: an outline eye, meaning only "view this leaf's sessions" — an outline like Start/
	   Backdate because it is an affordance the viewer takes, never a state. Deliberately distinct
	   from every glyph above: not Start (no play mark), not the stopwatch Active state, not a
	   readiness sign — this glyph is reserved for the Sessions action alone (plan §2.2). *@
	<symbol id="jt-icon-sessions" viewBox="0 0 16 16">
		<path d="M1 8S3.8 3.5 8 3.5 15 8 15 8s-2.8 4.5-7 4.5S1 8 1 8Z" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.4"
		      stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"/>
		<circle cx="8" cy="8" r="1.9" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.4"/>
	</symbol>
	<symbol id="jt-icon-archived" viewBox="0 0 16 16">
		<path d="M2 3.25c0-.41.34-.75.75-.75h10.5c.41 0 .75.34.75.75v1.5c0 .41-.34.75-.75.75H2.75A.75.75 0 0 1 2 4.75z"/>
		<path opacity="0.7" d="M3 7h10v5.25c0 .69-.56 1.25-1.25 1.25h-7.5C3.56 13.5 3 12.94 3 12.25z"/>
		<path d="M6.5 9.25h3" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.2" stroke-linecap="round"/>
	</symbol>
	<symbol id="jt-icon-github" viewBox="0 0 16 16">
		<path fill-rule="evenodd" clip-rule="evenodd"
		      d="M8 0C3.58 0 0 3.58 0 8c0 3.54 2.29 6.53 5.47 7.59.4.07.55-.17.55-.38 0-.19-.01-.82-.01-1.49-2.01.37-2.53-.49-2.69-.94-.09-.23-.48-.94-.82-1.13-.28-.15-.68-.52-.01-.53.63-.01 1.08.58 1.23.82.72 1.21 1.87.87 2.33.66.07-.52.28-.87.51-1.07-1.78-.2-3.64-.89-3.64-3.95 0-.87.31-1.59.82-2.15-.08-.2-.36-1.02.08-2.12 0 0 .67-.21 2.2.82.64-.18 1.32-.27 2-.27.68 0 1.36.09 2 .27 1.53-1.04 2.2-.82 2.2-.82.44 1.1.16 1.92.08 2.12.51.56.82 1.27.82 2.15 0 3.07-1.87 3.75-3.65 3.95.29.25.54.73.54 1.48 0 1.07-.01 1.93-.01 2.2 0 .21.15.46.55.38A8.01 8.01 0 0 0 16 8c0-4.42-3.58-8-8-8"/>
	</symbol>
</svg>
